article.headline: Montana 81, Eastern Wash. 54
article.story:
MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) -- The Lady Griz left little doubt from the
beginning that their Big Sky Conference semifinal game against
Eastern Washington wasn't going to be anything like Montana's 60-58
victory over the Eagles eight days earlier.

Montana powered to a 48-21 halftime lead and beat sixth-seeded
Eastern Washington 81-54 Friday night to advance to the
championship game of the Big Sky Conference tournament against
Idaho State, which beat Montana State 63-56 in the other semifinal.

Montana (26-4) takes a 16-game winning streak and a 21-game home
winning streak into the title game. The winner gets the league's
automatic berth in the NCAA tournament.

The University of Montana plays host to first- and second-round
games next weekend.

Hollie Tyler scored Montana's first nine points and finished
with 18 points, seven rebounds and five blocked shots in just 22
minutes of play.

"We were really ready," Tyler said. "They gave us a scare
last week. We had a lot of adrenaline going. We wanted to come out
and start well."

Katie Edwards added 13 points and Crystal Baird had 12.

"I love this team," said UM coach Robin Selvig. "It's deep
and we play well together. We've got a lot of defined roles. We
have people like Lynsey (Monaco) who can give us valuable minutes
in ways that don't show up on a stat sheet."

Monaco had three steals and four rebounds.

Big Sky MVP Brooklynn Lorenzen led the Lady Griz with 11 assists
and had just one turnover to go with six points.

Montana used a 12-0 run to take a 36-13 lead on a layup by Tyler
with 6:33 remaining and capped a 10-0 run with a basket by Baird to
take a 48-18 lead with 53 seconds left in the half.

EWU's Kathleen Nygaard had three 3-point plays to finish with
nine of her 14 points in the first half. She also had 11 rebounds.

"We're obviously pretty disappointed with our effort,
especially in the first half," said EWU coach Wendy Schuller.
"Montana played like a well-oiled machine and we didn't."

Selvig also noted that Jody McLeod had nine points and four key
rebounds in the first half.

"We emphasized rebounding after last week and (McLeod) was like
a rocket going up between some of those big girls," Selvig said.

Montana led 67-37 midway through the second half on a basket by
Julie Deming, who finished with seven points and four assists.

The Lady Griz built as much as a 36-point lead, the last time at
81-45 on a free throw by freshman Amy Brooks, who added eight
points.

"I wanted to get everybody involved in scoring," Tyler said.
"We've had games where everybody's done that and I think that's
just awesome."

The Eagles (13-16) didn't surpass Montana's first-half scoring
total until Nygaard's basket with 3:19 remaining to make the score
81-49.

Nygaard said she couldn't describe her team's frustration.

"I don't think you can put it into words," she said.

Joanna Chadd, who had 21 points in EWU's 58-57 first-round
victory over Weber State, was held scoreless on 0-of-7 shooting.

Julie Page fouled out with 14 points and eight rebounds for the
Eagles while Stephane Ulmer had 11 points.

Eastern Washington had 22 turnovers to Montana's eight. The Lady
Griz are second in the nation in fewest turnovers.
